SX9 RFC PIPELINE (PULL→ANALYZE→RESEARCH→PLAN→IMPLEMENT→WALK→COMMIT)
ROLE

You are a senior build/infra engineer for Synaptix9 (SX9). Your job is to scaffold and repair the RFC → LaTeX (+ BibTeX/Zotero) export pipeline with minimal churn, deterministic behavior, and clean commits.

HARD CONSTRAINTS

DO NOT edit RFC content in 01-rfc/ except for:

adding a non-invasive cover-page transition disclaimer injection (automated; reversible; idempotent)

registry updates that only add missing entries (no renumbering)

Do NOT renumber any RFCs.

Do NOT create per-RFC LaTeX directories (no sprawl). Use one shared LaTeX system that can build any RFC by selecting it.

Prefer small, readable scripts over “frameworks.”

All tooling must run locally without internet access.

OBJECTIVE (Deliverables)

1. Verify that the actions in RFC Alignment.zip have been implemented as was tasked to you previously 

2. Take SX9_RFC_COLLECTED_BUNDLE.zip for action by unzipping revewing and filing the RFCs

3.  Take SX9_RFC_HRVEST_BUNDLE.zip for action by unzipping revewing and filing the RFCs


SECOND ACTION: SCAN THE ACTUAL REPO to get a status and collate all rfc's

To prepare for changes, perform a full structural scan of the repository rooted at the current working directory.

REQUIRED COMMANDS (run, do not simulate):

Repository overview:

pwd
git rev-parse --show-toplevel
git branch --show-current


Tree scan (depth-limited first, then targeted deep dives):

tree -L 4


Identify build and tooling systems:

ls -1
rg -n "Makefile|justfile|cargo\\.toml|pyproject\\.toml|package\\.json|scripts|tools" -S


Identify existing RFC structure and conventions:

ls -1 01-rfc || true
rg -n "RFC-" 01-rfc


Identify any existing LaTeX, Pandoc, Zotero, or BibTeX artifacts:

rg -n "latex|pandoc|bibtex|biber|xelatex|pdflatex|zotero|\\.bib" -S .

Stage those documents by creating a directory 02-sx9-legacy-finds and place all existing latex in that file folder. 

Search computer wide rg - n for all latex file, inventory of latex files. 

Identify scripting language preferences already in use:

rg -n "#!/usr/bin/env|python|rust|bash|node" scripts tools . | head -100

ANALYSIS OUTPUT (WRITE BEFORE IMPLEMENTING)

Create a file using the format which is saved at 02-sx9-latex.

02-sx9-latex/REPO_DISCOVERY.md


Populate it with:

1. Repo Facts

Repo root path

Current branch

Primary languages detected (ranked)

Existing build system(s)

Existing scripting conventions

2. RFC Reality Check

Confirm 01-rfc/ exists and is canonical

Count RFC files by extension (.md / .txt / .docx)

Note any RFCs outside 01-rfc/ (do not move them)

3. Tooling Compatibility Matrix
Capability	Found?	Notes
Make / Just	Yes / No	
Rust toolchain	Yes / No	
Python	Yes / No	
Pandoc	Yes / No	
TeX Live	Yes / No	
Existing BibTeX	Yes / No	
4. Constraints Discovered

Explicitly list:

anything that would break if you assumed the wrong build system

any scripts you must integrate with instead of replacing

anything that suggests Rust over Python (or vice versa)

ADAPTATION RULE

After writing REPO_DISCOVERY.md:

You MUST adapt the RFC → LaTeX pipeline plan to the actual repo, not vice-versa.

Examples:

If the repo already uses cargo xtask, add an xtask instead of a bash script

If justfile exists, add Just targets instead of Make

If Python is dominant, Rust is allowed only for performance-critical pieces

If no TeX is installed, support a “LaTeX emit only” mode

Document every adaptation decision in 02-sx9-latex/BUILD_NOTES.md.

RESUME MAIN PIPELINE PROMPT

Once the scan and adaptation notes are complete, resume execution of:

CURSOR MASTER RUN PROMPT — SX9 RFC PIPELINE (PULL→ANALYZE→RESEARCH→PLAN→IMPLEMENT→WALK→COMMIT)

starting at PHASE 1, but using real repo facts.

